   <text>
      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers0421">
               <p>Member of an unmarried women&apos;s band at the Foundery from <date when="1742-04"
                     >Apr. 1742</date>, Clay was a leader of such a band from <date when="1742-11"
                     >Nov. 1742</date>, and a member of the select society from its beginning in
                     <date when="1743-12">Dec. 1743</date>. When <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> buried her remains on <date
                     when="1783-02-11">Feb. 11, 1783</date>, he spoke of her as &apos;the last of
                  those holy women who … forty years ago devoted themselves wholly to God&apos;
                        (<persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>, <hi
                     rend="italic">Works</hi>, 23:262). At his request she had written a spiritual
                  autobiography, which he published after her death. See <hi rend="italic">AM</hi> 6
                     (<date when="1783">1783</date>): 528ff.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
